## Migration Analysis

Your code has **two patterns** that break on .NET 8:

| API | Pattern | Replacement |
|-----|---------|-------------|
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | Blocking call interruption | `CancellationToken.WaitHandle` with `WaitHandle.WaitAny` |
| `Thread.Abort()` | Cancellable work loop | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` + cooperative check |

Both throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 6+ (`SYSLIB0006` / `SYSLIB0046`).

---

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class EventProcessor
{
    private readonly ManualResetEvent _newEvent = new ManualResetEvent(false);
    private readonly Queue<string> _queue = new Queue<string>();
    private Thread? _thread;
    private readonly object _lock = new object();
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        var token = _cts!.Token;
        var handles = new[] { _newEvent, token.WaitHandle };

        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // Blocks until either a new event arrives OR cancellation is requested
            int signaled = WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles);

            if (signaled == 1) // token.WaitHandle was signaled — stop requested
                break;

            _newEvent.Reset();

            string? item = null;
            lock (_lock)
            {
                if (_queue.Count > 0)
                    item = _queue.Dequeue();
            }

            if (item is not null)
                Handle(item);
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        lock (_lock) { _queue.Enqueue(item); }
        _newEvent.Set();
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts?.Cancel();          // Wakes RunLoop from WaitAny immediately
        _thread?.Join(5000);     // Wait up to 5s for graceful exit
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

---

## Key Changes Explained

1. **`WaitHandle.WaitAny(new[] { _newEvent, token.WaitHandle })`** — replaces bare `WaitOne()`. The thread now wakes on *either* a new event or a cancellation signal, eliminating the need for `Interrupt`.

2. **`token.IsCancellationRequested` loop guard** — the thread exits cooperatively. No forced termination needed.

3. **`_cts.Cancel()` replaces both `Interrupt` and `Abort`** — a single call unblocks the wait *and* signals the loop to exit.

4. **`_cts.Dispose()`** — avoids timer/callback leaks. Always dispose `CancellationTokenSource`.

---

## Pitfalls to Watch For

| Pitfall | Applies here? | Mitigation |
|---------|:---:|------------|
| `WaitOne()` doesn't respect cancellation tokens | ✅ | Replaced with `WaitHandle.WaitAny` including `token.WaitHandle` |
| Race: multiple items queued but only one dequeued per signal | ✅ (pre-existing bug) | Drain the queue in a loop after wake-up, or switch to `BlockingCollection<T>` |
| Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource` | ✅ | Added `_cts.Dispose()` in `Stop()` |
| `Handle(item)` runs long, delaying cancellation | ⚠️ | Pass `token` into `Handle` and check periodically if it does expensive work |
| Calling `Stop()` without `Start()` | ⚠️ | Null-conditional operators (`_cts?.Cancel()`) guard against this |

---

## Bonus: Even Simpler with `BlockingCollection<T>`

If you want a cleaner idiomatic .NET 8 approach that also fixes the race condition:

```csharp
public class EventProcessor
{
    private readonly BlockingCollection<string> _queue = new();
    private Thread? _thread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        try
        {
            foreach (var item in _queue.GetConsumingEnumerable(_cts!.Token))
                Handle(item);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException)
        {
            // Expected on shutdown — exit gracefully
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item) => _queue.Add(item);

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts?.Cancel();
        _thread?.Join(5000);
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _queue.Dispose();
    }
}
```

This eliminates the manual `ManualResetEvent`, `lock`, and `Queue` entirely — `BlockingCollection<T>` handles thread-safe producer/consumer with built-in cancellation support.
